Welcome to the W3C Privacy Interest Group, known as PING.

We are delighted to have you join us. Our mission is to improve privacy on the Web.

Everyone who is involved in the {{ group.name }} is expected to behave in accordance with the W3C Code of Conduct:
  https://www.w3.org/policies/code-of-conduct/

Our co-chairs are Pete Snyder (Invited Expert), Christine Runnegar (invited expert), and Nick Doty (CDT). Philippe Le Hegaret is our W3C contact.

A couple of items of information that may be helpful.

* You have been subscribed to the public W3C privacy activity email list, used by PING, public-privacy@w3.org.

* We also use the ping Slack channel on the w3ccommunity workspace. If you need an invite, use
  https://www.w3.org/slack-w3ccommunity-invite

* The group meets twice a month:
  https://auth.w3.org/?url=https://www.w3.org/groups/wg/{{ group.shortname }}/calendar

* PING is on Github  https://github.com/w3cping

    If you have not already done so, please link your GitHub and W3C accounts: https://www.w3.org/users/myprofile/connectedaccounts

* As background, you might want to read these two documents as they provide guidance to spec authors to help them reduce privacy risks and fingerprinting surface area in their specs:

    Privacy Principles - https://www.w3.org/TR/privacy-principles/

    Self-review questionnaire: Security and Privacy - https://www.w3.org/TR/security-privacy-questionnaire/

    Mitigating Browser Fingerprinting in Web Specifications - https://www.w3.org/TR/fingerprinting-guidance/

Everyone who is involved in PING is expected to behave in accordance with the W3C Code of Ethics and Professional Conduct (CEPC): https://www.w3.org/Consortium/cepc/

Christine, Nick, and Pete (co-chairs)
